App—Tantalus: son of Jupiter, and father of Pelops3 punished for betraying the secrets of the gods— Sisyphus: king of Corinth, famous for his cunning; slain by Theseus and condemned to eternal punishment; cf. Hor. Carm. ΙΙ. 14. 20; Hom. Od. XI. 593-600. The quotation, in dac- tylic hexameters, is probably from Lucilius. Final s of Sisyphus does not make position. — Minos et Rhadamanthus: Minos, king of Crete, and Rhadamanthus his brother were noted in life for jus- tice. For this reason, according to fable, they, with Aeacus, were made judges in the lower world. —L. Crassus . . . M. Antonius: see ita magnos, 5 n. Crassus and Antonius were the leading speakers in the de Oratore. — tibi . . . te : note the grouping of pronouns. —-
